@colemanja91 Yes, I think you are correct in terms of the two approaches. I think I have a preference for the constant collection and using Counters.

One potential approach that I think might be interesting is to actually hook into the event handlers logic that already exists. The scheduler would just trigger events when they happen, and you would have something `contrib.prometheus` or `contrib.newrelic` modules that register a number of event handlers and could deal with them as they want. Which of those modules actually gets imported would be controlled by a configuration setting.

I think that doesn't couple the scheduler code too tightly with any one metric collection tool, and provides lots of flexibility.  The only thing that wouldn't be possible is adding your own custom events to the scheduler, but I'm not sure that there is any reasonable solution to that problem (or if it is really a problem at all)

@carljm Got it. Its triggered by any call to [`collections.MutableMapping.register`](

```python
import collections


class MyMapping(collections.Mapping):
    _store = {
        'KEY1': 'looked up key 1',
        'KEY2': 'looked up key 2',
        'KEY3': 'looked up key 3',
    }

    def __getitem__(self, key):
        return self._store[key]

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self._store)

    def __iter__(self):
        return iter(self._store)


collections.MutableMapping.register(MyMapping)
```

