@rmandelb , I think your logic is sound.

I'm not sure if having the zeropoint mean "magnitude producing 1 photon/sec in this telescope" or "magnitude producing 1 photon/sec/cm^2 independent of telescope" is more typical.  I think the main advantage of using the latter definition is that it makes using the `area` kwarg in `drawImage` simpler, since you don't need to know what collecting area was used to set the bandpass zeropoint in that case.  Adding a kwarg to `withZeropoint` to handle convert from ACS-style definition to GalSim-style definition is probably a good idea.  Regardless of what we do, one convention that I think is worth maintaining (and potentially testing for if we aren't doing it already), is that SED amplitudes should be totally independent of telescope and exposure times, including setting their amplitudes via `withMagnitude`.

In theory, there's some documentation in demo12 in addition to demo13.  I see there that the `withFluxDensity` description there is a lie(!) though.  It should say "we normalize such that the photon density is 1 photon per nm per cm^2 per s" instead of just "1 photon per nm".  We could definitely use a more extensive demo for setting `SED` fluxes/magnitudes/flux-densities, `Bandpass` zeropoints, using the `drawImage` `area` and `exptime` kwargs, and using the `RealGalaxy` and `ChromaticRealGalaxy` `area_norm` kwarg.  I think a jupyter notebook might actually be a nice way to present this.

