Because overriding `CodeCell.prototype.get_text`has a number of side effects (e.g. the added meta information would be saved to notebook), I ended up modifying `cell.kernel.execute` as follows

```
        var my_execute = function (code, callbacks, options) {
            "use strict"
            var cells = IPython.notebook.get_cells();
            for (var i = cells.length - 1; i >= 0;  --i ) {
                // cells being executed would have input prompt '*' according
                // to this.set_input_prompt('*') before execute is called.
                // Also, because a cell might start executing without a previous cell
                // being finished, we should start from reverse and check actual code
                // A magic is used to send meta information and cell index to the kernel
                if (cells[i].input_prompt_number == '*' && code == cells[i].get_text()) {
                   return this.orig_execute(
                        "%softwith " + cells[i].metadata.kernel + " --cell " + i.toString() + "\n" + code,
                        callbacks, options)
                }
            }
        }
        // override kernel execute with the wrapper.
        IPython.notebook.kernel.orig_execute = IPython.notebook.kernel.execute
        IPython.notebook.kernel.execute = my_execute
```

The code also sends cell index to the kernel which also solves problem 1 (locate just executed cell). It is a hack and it is not particularly efficient (search notebook for each `execute` call) also I would be happy to switch if there is a better way to send meta data to kernel for execution (it looks like `user_expression` could be used for this).

IMO `api.one` comes with some other potential issues that aren't described there. Admittedly I don't fully understand the cache + ORM, but the below is an anti-pattern enforced by this API that I see quite often - it feels very much like n+1:

```
@api.one
def one_meth(self):
    self.multi_meth()

@api.multi
def multi_meth(self):
    # Do some stuff
    self.write(vals)
```

